From: av-stack integration <baonguyenpro@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 08 Jul 2026 07:44:32 +0700
Subject: [PATCH] ara::com: fix use-after-move in Serializer<std::vector<T>>::DeserializeAt

Optional::Value() && disengages the optional (nulls the value pointer), so
accessing elemResult.Value().second AFTER std::move(elemResult).Value().first
throws std::runtime_error("Optional contains no value.") on the FIRST element
of every non-trivially-copyable vector payload.

Observed on target (av-stack, Jetson Orin Nano, vsomeip binding):
  * proxy-side event deserialization of any vector payload threw per sample;
    inside vsomeip receive handlers the exception was swallowed by
    application_impl::invoke_handler (app alive but received nothing),
  * in an app main loop (GetNewSamples) it escaped and hit std::terminate.

Take the pair out of the Result once, then use both members. The map
serializer below already does this in the correct order.
---
diff --git a/src/ara/com/serialization.h b/src/ara/com/serialization.h
index d6f4e0b..9a3b617 100644
--- a/src/ara/com/serialization.h
+++ b/src/ara/com/serialization.h
@@ -395,8 +395,11 @@ namespace ara
                         return core::Result<std::pair<std::vector<T>, std::size_t>>::
                             FromError(elemResult.Error());
                     }
-                    result.push_back(std::move(elemResult).Value().first);
-                    offset += elemResult.Value().second;
+                    // Take the pair out ONCE: Optional::Value()&& disengages the
+                    // optional, so a second elemResult.Value() would throw.
+                    auto elem = std::move(elemResult).Value();
+                    result.push_back(std::move(elem.first));
+                    offset += elem.second;
                 }
 
                 return core::Result<std::pair<std::vector<T>, std::size_t>>::
